<br>
Anyone thats been to Hate have any advice?  Thanks...also any general Hate advice for druids would be awesome<br>
<br>
Tuladen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukatlynel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Katlynel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/13/01 2:50:37 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.asianavenue.com/indiegrrl/faedrake.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Plane of Hate question</span><hr size=1> Same advice as on any large raid, really.  Watch backup heals on the chanters and clerics (and other crunchy types), thorns on the main tank, strength buffs on the rogues.  If you're the only druid, it may or may not be your responsibility to snare; you should establish this beforehand by talking to the rangers and necros on the raid (since necro dark will overwrite your snare).  If there's a ranger going of higher level than you, ask her/him if s/he will take snare duty since they'll generate less aggro than you will, being higher level.  Also at a higher level they'll have better odds of landing the snare, and since they won't be sitting the way you will, they'll draw less aggro.<br>
<br>
You can use ONE of the following THREE spells, and no matter which one you use, you should wait until the main tank has had a few seconds to buidl some aggro.  Do NOT use more than one or you will get pounded in to the ground.<br>
1) Ensnare / Snare<br>
2) Ro's Fiery Sundering<br>
3) Fixation of Ro<br>
Which one you use will depend on whether you need to snare (duh), whether you have a lot of melees, or whether you have a lot of people using fire based nukes (wizards/mages/druids). <p><font face="Verdana, Arial" size="2">
Katlynel Wolfcaller
<BR>58 Preserver, Saryrn
</font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaeresilverwolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saere Silverwolf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/13/01 3:44:52 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Plane of Hate question</span><hr size=1> I agree with what Katlynel said.  Kat also said it's the same advice as a large raid and it also depends on the kind of make up (class-wise) your raid has.  I totally agree and just want to add that being a druid, you may not ever really know your role until you get in there.  Warriors will just hit on things, wizards and mages will just nuke, clerics will always just heal... but being a druid you will get to diversify a little bit.  You just never know.  :)  <br>
<br>
On the last Hate raid I went to, I was the only druid there and since I wasn't in the puller group or with the main or secondary assist, pack chloro was kind of going to waste on my group.  I did nuke a little bit and snare was not my responsibility that evening.  The majority of my evening was watching out for the enchanters and clerics -- especially the clerics who did not have a backup healer in their group.  <br>
<br>
I didn't learn this trick until a month ago (how embarrassing lol  /bonks herself) so I'll just share it for anyone who hasn't heard it yet either.  This worked really well in the planes.  If you type /target &lt;player&gt; it will target the person if they are close enough to you.  I can't believe I didn't know that!  lol  So during fights I would /target the enchanters and clerics that every so often would get beat on - you'll find that there is usually one cleric and one enchanter that is normally taking a beating for one reason or another and you'll know to target them during each fight.  Keep targeting them and be their back up heal if you have to.  The single chloro spell got a lot of use for chanters and clerics.  <br>
<br>
People were also laughing because I was sowing.  I mean you're in hate -- where are you going to run?  hehehe  But still, some people asked for it.  *shrug*<br>
<br>
Honestly I haven't been on a lot of plane raids so I am not the be-all of advice in this area, but what I can say is don't get too hung up on your level or get worried about having to do a lot of damage... that's not really what you're there for.  I was surprised at how clerics and enchanters appreciated the things I consider trivial -- things like chloroplast and sows.  <br>
<br>
And most of all -- have fun.  :) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubrairwolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brairwolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/13/01 4:10:33 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Plane of Hate question</span><hr size=1> In hate I have found it a very very bad idea to even mem fixation of ro.<br>
