<br>
AND HAVE FUN!!! <p><img src=http://home1.gte.net/chiefq/signamesmall.gif></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(7/14/01 6:17:09 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Plane of Hate question</span><hr size=1> A couple of pointers for high level groups, since there are some things that don't necessarily carry over from your lower leveling grouping habits.  These pointers apply to any Planes raid, Sebilis, dragons, etc.<br>
<br>
1. Check with the target, esp. the main tank, before you cast any buff on them, including spikes.  Sometimes the main tank doesn't want your spikes...especially if there are multiple summoning mobs.   The tanks know all about spikes, and know who to ask for it.<br>
<br>
2. Check with your group before casting a group buff.  Sometimes our group buffs overwrite or prevent other beneficial spells from taking effect.  For example, I warn my groups before casting PoG, so the wizards can all get far away or disband, as   PoG conflicts with their epic weapon effect and they usually don't want it.  <br>
<br>
3. Don't buff for the sake of buffing.  Many of our buffs have better versions cast by other classes, and it's a waste of mana.  Certain buffs also have to be cast in the correct order due to stacking conflicts, and you don't want to cast yours until the right time. And sometimes that minor buff you cast can prevent needed buffs from being cast on the player due to the 15 buff limitation.<br>
<br>
4. The above also applies to SoWing.  As noted in other responses, SoW is not needed in many high level raids, and takes up a valuable buff slot.  Also, most folks at this level have j-boots or some similar ability to get SoW speed, so it's not really necessary.  Of course, there are some encounters with mobs faster than j-boots but slower than a high level SoW where your SoW will be requested...:)<br>
<br>
5. Check with your group to determine if an evac should be ready to cast.  Most often, you won't need it for high level raids, where the philosophy is to die 'n' res in place.  And find out who is going to call for an evac if you do have it up.  <br>
<br>
6. Check to determine if your healing powers are needed at all.  That's a function of your level, the levels of the other folks in the raid, and the number of clerics available.   On a typical multi-group raid, I rarely heal.  I do some prelim buffing, cast ensnare and RFS, and then try to inflict damage.  I do some healing if the mob is totally resistant to any magic, or if we are a bit low on clerics.  <br>
<br>
7. Know who the main assist is in multiple mob situations.  As stated above, make a button with /assist whoever-is-the-main-assist.  Before casting any sort of spell that could disrupt or prevent mezzing, hit that button a few times to make sure that the targetted mob is the right one.  A good rule of thumb is to see if there is any damage to that mob.  This is especially important for DoTs, because your DoT will prevent the mob from being mezzed.  That will piss off the chanter, and they won't cast C2 on you anymore...:)<br>
<br>
If you have any doubts, don't cast.  Or stick with DD type spells where, if you make a mistake, the mob can be re-mezzed.<br>
<br>
